References: <387EA510-2FD7-4508-8EC9-C7D4C646DD1A@gmail.com>
 <ec1602f2-22e9-8651-8806-7234c17b4d92@fredhutch.org>
 <BL0PR04MB660936FE03D46D4EAA74B8ADF9CC0@BL0PR04MB6609.namprd04.prod.outlook.com>
 <F4F5148F-8002-491F-9003-75C39DAEBA59@gmail.com>
Message-ID: <BL0PR04MB66096263EC079B8D07F5C41BF9CD0@BL0PR04MB6609.namprd04.prod.outlook.com>

I see that seqlogo and MotIV are not listed in the DESCRIPTION file as dependencies; since they are used in the vignette only they should be listed as Suggests:

I don't think there's value in trying to eliminate all dependencies. One really does want to re-use robust, tested code rather than writing new code that is likely full of bugs (speaking for my own code, at least!), making subtle implementation decisions that impede interoperability, etc. Also I think an important part of Bioconductor is interoperability, and illustrating that in vignettes / examples sounds very reasonable.

Instead I guess there is a trade-off -- is a particular feature worth 100 additional packages? Is there an alternative, maybe less comprehensive, implementation that does not require re-inventing the wheel? Etc. Probably there is a synergy -- if the package you'd like to depend on were implemented more conservatively, perhaps it would not carry such a dependency load. Maybe also as disciplines mature it becomes easier to re-factor packages into compact reusable cores and user-facing niceties.

I know that Mike Love has taken DESeq2 on a dependency diet, from 120 in release to 93 in devel, and there has not been an outcry of missing features. So there is hope...

Martin


?On 3/27/20, 10:14 AM, "Paul Shannon" <paul.thurmond.shannon at gmail.com> wrote:

    Thanks, Herve.  Thanks, Martin.
    
    In the devel version, I added a method to MotifDb for matching motif to sequence - a small, useful addition I thought. 
    
    The core dump (thanks for the analysis, Martin) seems to come in the call to motifmatchr::matchMotifs, which wraps the C++ MOODS library, and forms the core of my new method.  See below.
    
    MotifDb acquired other new dependencies as well, which needed to transform MotifDb native matrices into the form motifmatchr expects.
    
    This capability -seemed- like a sensible addition to the package. But not so much any more.  I will remove it, and whittle the dependencies down to a minimum. 
     
    Which leads to this broader question:  should I eliminate every dependency I can? 
    
    For instance, two long-standing dependencies in MotifDb are seqlogo and MotIV.  Neither are needed by the package.  They appear only in the vignette to illustrate some the things that MotifDb enables.  Is there an approved Bioc documentation style for describing these related uses without incurring the dependencies that comes with executable code?  If so, I could use that approach to explain motifmatchr as well.
    
     - Paul
    
    setMethod('matchMotif', signature='MotifList',
    
       function(object, motifs, genomeName, regions, pval.cutoff, fimoDataFrameStyle=FALSE){
         motifs.pfmatrix <- lapply(motifs, function(motif) convert_motifs(motif, "TFBSTools-PFMatrix"))
         motifs.pfmList <- do.call(PFMatrixList, motifs.pfmatrix)
         gr.list <- motifmatchr::matchMotifs(motifs.pfmList, regions, genome=genomeName, 
                                             out="positions", p.cutoff=pval.cutoff)
         result <- gr.list
         if(fimoDataFrameStyle){
            gr <- unlist(gr.list)
            motif.names <- names(gr)
            names(gr) <- NULL
            tbl <- as.data.frame(gr)
            tbl$motif_id <- motif.names
            colnames(tbl)[1] <- "chrom"
            tbl$chrom <- as.character(tbl$chrom)
            colnames(tbl)[grep("score", colnames(tbl))] <- "mood.score"
            new.order <- order(tbl$start, decreasing=FALSE)
            tbl <- tbl[new.order,]
            result <- tbl
            }
         return(result)
         })
    
    
    
